mong both countries' casino dealers, pit bosses, and politicians. While the popular imagination sees the Nevada casino as a hedonistic world of consumption, The Labor of Luck shows that the "Vegas experience" is made possible only through a variety of systems regulating labor, capital, and consumers, and that because of these complex dynamics, the Vegas casino cannot be seamlessly picked up and replicated elsewhere. Sallaz's fresh and path-breaking approach reveals how neo-liberal versus post-colonial forms of governance produce divergent worlds at the tables, and how politics, profits, and pleasure have come together to shape everyday life in the new economy.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 29. Mai 2023) 0aCasinoszSouth Africa. 0aCasinoszUnited States. 7aSOCIAL SCIENCE / Anthropology / Cultural & Social.2bisacsh  aafrica.  aamerican casinos.  abusiness and industry.  abusiness.  acapitalism.  acasino capitalism.  acasino dealers.  acasino industry.  acasino management.  acomparative ethnography.  aconsumerism.  aeconomic history.  aethnography.  aglobal casino.  agold city casino.  alabor studies.  alas vegas.  aneoliberalism.  anorth america.  apit bosses.  apolitical history.  apostcolonialism.  apower and wealth.  aregulated labor.  aregulations.  asilver state casino.  asociology.  asouth africa.  asouth african casinos.  aunited states of america.  avegas experience.  awork and labor.08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertUniversity of California Press Backlist Package 2000-2013z97831106904220 cprintz978052025948540uhttps://doi.org/10.1525/978052094465740uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780520944657423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780520944657/original  a978-3-11-069042-2  University of California Press Backlist P